text.data-name: From our interviews, we found that caring is really a personal matter, and people have really different approaches when it comes to intimacy. For instance, some users prefer really spontaneous call with their parents, while some would think twice and sche
text.tspan: From our interviews, we found that caring is really a personal matter, and people have really different approaches
when it comes to intimacy. For instance, some users prefer really spontaneous call with their parents, while some
would think twice and schedule calls carefully. It might be challenging to find out a universal solution.
We also found that our users did not have a strong demand for a new tool for caring about their parents. "Well,
Whatsapp is definitely not the best but it's fine, I really don't know what I can expect..." We realized user needs can be
really vague and it is our role to figure out a solution based on what we learned so far.

text.data-name: Our interviewees have completely different approaches when dealing with their relationship with their parents.
Our interviewees were mostly satisfied with their current tools to communicate with their parents.

We conducted 5 interviews with expats living in Europe to tell us about how they communicate with and take care of their parents, and what aspects they worry mostly about their parents when they live abroad.

text.data-name: "After forming user requirements, we took a look back and found that our target group was a little vague. We aimed to design for 'expats living abroad who need to take care of their parents', but is it more like for 'people who need to take care of their e
text.tspan: "After forming user requirements, we took a look back and found that our target group was a little vague. We
aimed to design for 'expats living abroad who need to take care of their parents', but is it more like for 'people who
need to take care of their elderly parents' now?"
However, design is about tradeoffs, and it is the designer's obligation to decide what choices are provided to users
and what the system should offer. This finding reminded us about design trade-offs and thus during ideation and
brainstorming, we tried to cover different requirements but ensure the functionalities and positioning are
relatively specific at the same time.

The testing also showed that users started to notice some navigation and flow issues, which provided us with

As we recruited some of the users from our previous paper testing for the digital testing, we also found that
compared to other users, these users were more willing to contribute and suggest improvements for our
prototype, which suggests that they had more product ownership than others.
